[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering test framework**\n\nI need to create a FrameworkLoggerTest and figure out the log4j stubs. Using nested classes could complicate package naming, so maybe actual dependency would be simpler. I wonder about the log4j-api version and its vulnerabilities. Adding it might introduce unnecessary dynamic accesses, but I want to focus on testing the active class. I also need to think about creating package-private classes for better scoping. However, the dedicated test must remain in its specific package. So many considerations!\n\n**Clarifying test class structure**\n\nI want to support Level, Logger, and LogManager in the same file as package-private top-level classes. My main concern is whether Class.getMethod only returns public methods. If a class is package-private but has a public method, I think Class.getMethod should still return it. However, invoking it from FrameworkLogger may lead to an IllegalAccessException. \n\nI realize that in Java, there's only one public top-level class per file, so I could make support classes public but nested. I wonder if using separate public files might be more straightforward for testing.\n\n**Implementing static initialization**\n\nI’m considering that the static initialization of FrameworkLogger might occur before any reference to the stub classes. The test class can reference Level.class and others, but I need to ensure that when FrameworkLogger first loads, Class.forName will correctly find those stubs. \n\nTo achieve this, I think I need to implement a stub for Level that includes the toLevel method to record the requested names. This feels crucial for ensuring everything links up correctly.\n\n**Checking test dependencies**\n\nI'm wondering if the test runtime classpath could include log4j. I need to check dependencies closely. There's a possibility that our test source class, org.apache.logging.log4j.Logger,